  9  # Preservation and reflection of (co)limits.
 10  
 11  There are various distinct notions of "preserving limits". The one we
 12  aim to capture here is: A functor F : C â†’ D "preserves limits" if it
 13  sends every limit cone in C to a limit cone in D. Informally, F
 14  preserves all the limits which exist in C.
 15  
 16  Note that:
 17  
 18  * Of course, we do not want to require F to *strictly* take chosen
 19    limit cones of C to chosen limit cones of D. Indeed, the above
 20    definition makes no reference to a choice of limit cones so it makes
 21    sense without any conditions on C or D.
 22  
 23  * Some diagrams in C may have no limit. In this case, there is no
 24    condition on the behavior of F on such diagrams. There are other
 25    notions (such as "flat functor") which impose conditions also on
 26    diagrams in C with no limits, but these are not considered here.
 27  
 28  In order to be able to express the property of preserving limits of a
 29  certain form, we say that a functor F preserves the limit of a
 30  diagram K if F sends every limit cone on K to a limit cone. This is
 31  vacuously satisfied when K does not admit a limit, which is consistent
 32  with the above definition of "preserves limits".
